\section{Introduction}

\lettrine[nindent=0em,lines=3]{A}ntennae are vital parts of modern infrastructure. They are used to both transmit and receive signals, for detection of objects but also for data transmission. This article will deal with the basic principles behind electromagnetic radiation, antennae, noise reduction and antenna directivity.


%------------------------------------------------

\section{Electromagnetic radiation}
Electromagnetic radiation is comprised of two parts: an oscillating electric field and an oscillating magnetic field. These two fields are spatially perpendicular to each other, but both propagate linea recta in the same direction, perpendicular to the directions of both the electric and magnetic components of the radiation. This is illustrated in figure \ref{F:elec_mag_field}.

\begin{Figure}
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{Images/elec_mag_field.png}
	\captionof{figure}{Electric and magnetic field components and direction of propagation of electromagnetic radiaton. Image credit: \url{http://www.ndt-ed.org}.}
	\label{F:elec_mag_field}
\end{Figure}

This radiation is characterized using several measures:
\begin{itemize}
	\item Amplitude: The units for the amplitude of the electric and magnetic components are different, but we measure electric fields in Newton per Coulomb, and the magnetic field in Tesla.
	\item Frequency: Sometimes wavelength is used for the same purpose. Both indicate the periodicity of the signal: how much time/space is needed for the wave to fully cycle through its phases. Frequency is the inverse of the time that is needed and is therefore an indication of how many times per unit time the signal is periodic.
	\item Polarization: The direction of the electric field component of the electromagnetic wave. This can be a fixed direction, but this can also be periodic or random.
\end{itemize}

For the purposes of this article the electric field component of the electromagnetic wave will be relevant, as described in the next section "Antenna Principles" (Section \ref{sec:antenna_principles}) . The electric component of an electromagnetic wave can be described using the following equation (equation \ref{eq:elec_field}): 

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:elec_field}
	E = E_0 \cdot \cos{(\theta)} \cdot e^{i \cdot 2 \pi \cdot \nu \cdot t + \phi_0}
\end{align}
Where $E$ is the electric field in a certain direction in Newton/Coulomb, $E_0$ is the amplitude of the electric field component of the incoming electromagnetic radiation in Newton/Coulomb, $\theta$ is the angle between the direction in which we are measuring and the polarization of the incoming electromagnetic wave at the measured position in radians, $\nu$ is the frequency of the electromagnetic wave in Hertz, $t$ is the time at which we're measuring in seconds and $\phi_0$ is the phase of the electric field in radians at $t = 0$. 

These principles and equation \ref{eq:elec_field} will be used extensively throughout the rest of this text. 

Electromagnetic radiation is used extensively throughout modern technology for the transmission of data. For this purpose, a transmitter encodes data onto a carrier wave by either changing the carrier wave's amplitude (known as Amplitude Modulation) or by changing the carrier wave's frequency slightly (known as Frequency Modulation). The sent data is then encoded onto these changes.

