\section{Potential in Dipole}
Every antenna type has a different potential difference created on its terminal(s) resulting from incoming electromagnetic radiation. In this section we will first develop an equation that describes this potential difference resulting from harmonic electromagnetic radiation based on work by K.T. McDonald \cite{verg13} . We will then look into more general forms of electromagnetic radiation.

\subsection{Potential due to harmonic electromagnetic radiation}
This subsection is based and largely taken from work by K.T. McDonald \cite{verg13} from Princeton University.
The  electric field component from incident electromagnetic radiation for a harmonic radiation source can be described for linearly polarized light with polarization in the $\hat{z}$ direction by equation \ref{eq:Efieldantenna}. This derivation will assume an antenna with half-height $h$.

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:Efieldantenna}
	\vec{E_{in}} = E_0 \cdot e^{-i \left( kx - \omega t\right)} \hat{z}
\end{align} 

Where $E_0$ is the electric field amplitude in the $\hat{z}$ direction, $k$ is the wave's wave number, t is the time of measurement and $\omega$ is the angular frequency of the radiation. This electric field oscillates as described in section \ref{sec:antenna_principles} a current distribution in the antenna's wires. This oscillates with the same (angular) frequency as does the incoming electric field as described in equation \ref{eq:currentAntenna}.

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:currentAntenna}
	\vec{J} \left(\vec{r}, t  \right) = \vec{J} \left(\vec{r} \right) \cdot e^{i \omega t}
\end{align}

Where $\vec{J}$ is the current distribution in the wire. The retarded vector potential for this current distribution is described by equation \ref{eq:retardedvectorpotential}.

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:retardedvectorpotential}
	\vec{A} \left( \vec{r}, t \right) &= \vec{A} \left( \vec{r} \right) \cdot e^{i \omega t} \\
	&= \frac{\mu_0}{4 \pi} \int \frac{\vec{J} \left( \vec{r}', t' \equiv t - \scriptr{r} / c\right)}{\scriptr{r} } \; d \tau \\ 
	&= \frac{\mu_0}{4 \pi} \int \vec{J} \left( \vec{r}' \right) \frac{e^{ik \scriptr{r}}}{\scriptr{r}} d \tau e^{i \omega t} \\
	&= \vec{A} \left( \vec{r} \right) \cdot e^{i \omega t}
\end{align}

Where $\scriptr{r}$ is the distance from source to position of the volume element and $\mu_0$ is the vacuum permeability. Since our antenna consists of a very thin wire oriented in the $\hat{z}$ direction, we know that the current density is well approximated by a current $I(z)$. Therefore, the vector potential only has a $z$ component in cylindrical co\"ordinates  ($\rho$, $\phi$, $z$) as illustrated in equation \ref{eq:vecpotz}.

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:vecpotz}
	A_z \left( \vec{r} \right) = \frac{\mu_0}{4 \pi} \int I(z') \frac{e^{-ik \scriptr{r}} }{\scriptr{r}} \; dz'
\end{align}
We know that according to the Lorenz gauge equation \ref{eq:lorenzgauge} must hold for the vector potential of the current distribution and the potential of the charge distribution.

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:lorenzgauge}
	\vec{\nabla} \vec{A} + \frac{1}{c^2} \frac{\partial V}{\partial t} = 0
\end{align}

With $V$ the scalar potential of the response field: $V(\vec{r},t) = V)(\vec{r}) e^{i\omega t}$.
These two fields are therefore related according to equation \ref{eq:vecpotelpot}.

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:vecpotelpot}
	V(\vec{r}) = \frac{i c}{k} \frac{\partial A_z(\vec{r})}{\partial z} \equiv \frac{ic}{k} \; \partial_z A_z(\vec{r})
\end{align}
 
The response electric and magnetic fields, $\vec{E}\left(\vec{r}, t \right) = \vec{E}\left(\vec{r} \right) e^{i\omega t}$ and $\vec{B}\left(\vec{r}, t \right) = \vec{B}\left(\vec{r} \right) e^{i\omega t}$ respectively can thus be calculated from the vector potential $A_z(\vec{r})$ as described in equations \ref{eq:elrespfield} and \ref{eq:magrespfield}. 

\begin{align}
	\vec{E}(\vec{r}) &= - \vec{\nabla}V(\vec{r} - i\omega\vec{A}(\vec{r})	 \\
	\label{eq:elrespfield}
	&= -\frac{ic}{k} \left[ \partial^2_{r,z} A_z(\vec{r} \hat{\rho} _+ \left( \partial^2_z + k^2 \right) A_z(\vec{r}) \hat{z} \right]
\end{align}

\begin{align}
	\vec{B}(\vec{r}) &= \vec{\nabla} \times \vec{A}(\vec{r}) \\
	\label{eq:magrespfield}
	&= - \partial_{\rho} A_z (\vec{r}) \hat{\phi}
\end{align}

We know that as a boundary condition the total electric field at the surface, $\vec{E}_{in} +\vec{E}$ of the conducting wires must have no tangential component. For a thin wire such as in our case this means that the $z$ component of the total electric field, parallel to our antenna, must vanish, as illustrated by the requirement on the resulting electric field from the charge distribution in the wire in equation \ref{eq:nozcomp}.

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:nozcomp}
	E_z(0, 0, z) = - E_{in} = - E_0
\end{align}

If we say that there's a finite distance between the closest ends of the two parts of the dipole antenna, as illustrated in section \ref{sec:Dipole}, which we shall call $d$, with $d \ll h$.
 Using equation \ref{eq:elrespfield} we find a differential equation for the vector potentials in the space between the two wires, as described in equation \ref{eq:diffeqpotbetweenwires}. 
 
\begin{align}
	\label{eq:diffeqpotbetweenwires}
	\left( \partial^2_z + k^2 \right) A_z (0, 0, z) &= \frac{ik}{c} E_z(0, 0, 0)  \\
	&= - \frac{ik}{c} E_0 
\end{align}

Solutions to the homogeneous differential equation are 0, $\cos{kz}$ and $\sin{kz}$, whereas the inhomogeneous part has $\frac{-i E_0}{kc}$ as a solution. The general solution is therefore as described in equation \ref{eq:gensoldiffeqpotbetweenwires}.

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:gensoldiffeqpotbetweenwires}
	\begin{split}
	A_z(0, &0, d/2 \le z \le h) = \\
	&C_1 \cos{kz} + C_2 \sin{kz} - \frac{i E_0}{kc}
	\end{split}
\end{align}

Due to symmetry considerations we expect the vector potential will be symmetric about $z = 0$. So the solution for the interval $[-h, -d/2]$ can be written as in equation \ref{eq:solutionbelowzis0}. 

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:solutionbelowzis0}
	\begin{split}
	A_z(0, &0, -h \le z \le -d/2) = \\
	&C_1 \cos{kz} - C_2 \sin{kz} - \frac{i E_0}{kc}
	\end{split}
\end{align}

We need additional conditions for our system if we are to determine the constants $C_1, C_2$. We note that for a circuit with no load attached to the antenna terminals, the current $I(z)$ must vanish at the ends of the conducting wires, explicitly at $z = -h, -d/2, d/2$ and $h$. We know that for a thin-wire the vector potential on the wire is proportional to the current in the wire at that point. For the thin-wire approximation, the needed conditions are such that the vector potential also vanishes at the aforementioned ends of the conducting wires. This gives us for our constants $C_1, C_2$ the equations \ref{eq:c1} and \ref{eq:c2}.

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:c1}
	C_1 = \frac{i E_0}{kc}
\end{align}

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:c2}
	C_2 = - \frac{i E_0}{kc} \frac{1 - \cos{kh}}{\sin{kh}}
\end{align}

Combining these with equation \ref{eq:vecpotelpot} gives is the potential difference accross the terminals as described in equation \ref{eq:potterminals}.

\begin{align}
	\label{eq:potterminals}
	\begin{split}
		V_{\mbox{term}} &= V(0, 0, d/2) - V(0, 0, -d/2)  \\
		&= \frac{ic}{k} \left( A'_z(0,0,d/2) - A'_z(0,0,-d/2) \right) \\
		&= 2 ic C_2 = - \frac{2 E_0}{k} \frac{1 - \cos{kh}}{\sin{kh}}
	\end{split}
\end{align}

Or alternatively the full form:
\begin{align}
	\label{eq:potterminalsfull}
	\begin{split}
	&V_{\mbox{term}}(t) =  \\
	&- \frac{2 E_0}{k} \frac{1 - \cos{kh}}{\sin{kh}} \cdot \cos{\theta} \cdot e^{i \omega (t - d/c) + \phi_0}
	\end{split}
\end{align}
With $d$ the distance from antenna to source. 

Equation \ref{eq:potterminalsfull} will be used extensively throughout the rest of this article. The signal that this equation gives can be seen in figure \ref{F:sig_lin_harm_nonoise}.

