\section{Directivity}
\label{sec:directivity}
In the previous sections the discussed scenarios merely include sources, both intended and noise, at ideal perpendicular angles, along the defined axis. As stated in equation \ref{eq:elec_field} the sensitivity decreases by a factor $\cos{\theta}$ where $\theta$ is the angle between the orientations of the antenna and the direction of propagation of the signal. In a dual dipole configuration the sensitivity in the defined xz-plane is dependent on this relationship. The interdependent sensitivity in the yz-plane however is a more complex combination of the sensitivity of both antennae and the difference in phase caused by their mutual distance along the signals direction of propagation. The combined effect of the aforementioned dependencies can best be visualized in a directivity plot, such as in figure \ref{F:directivitysingledipoleparallel}. The body of a directivity plot represents the antennas sensitivity in every direction as for every data point its distance to the center is proportional to the antennas sensitivity in the corresponding direction.

